ot add record-kind filtering. Return ordered records\n+with clear `kind`, `role`, `tool_name`, and redacted text fields. The consuming\n+agent can decide to skim tool calls, skip noisy tool results, or read them when\n+tests/errors/commands matter.\n+\n+## Expected Agent Access Pattern\n+\n+When a user asks an agent to catch up with a branch, the agent should not try to\n+load everything. A good workflow is:\n+\n+1. Resolve the current branch or requested branch.\n+2. Run `but agentlog sessions branch <branch>`.\n+3. Pick likely useful sessions from outline data:\n+   - prefer recent sessions\n+   - prefer sessions with incremental turns over one-off sidecar backfills\n+   - inspect sidecar sessions only when their previews look relevant\n+4. Run `but agentlog timeline <session-key> --limit 20` for the most promising\n+   session.\n+5. Read records from selected turns:\n+   - latest incremental turns first\n+   - tail of a large backfill when the backfill is the only evidence\n+   - head of a backfill only if the original task prompt is unclear\n+6. Read adjacent or older turns only if the first pass leaves gaps.\n+\n+The agent's natural unit of navigation is the capture turn, not individual\n+records. Records are the rendering layer once a turn has been selected.\n+\n+Tool calls and tool results should stay visible but not dominate the workflow.\n+In practice, the agent should scan:\n+\n+- user messages for intent and corrections\n+- assistant messages for decisions, plans, and final status\n+- tool calls for files inspected, commands run, and tests attempted\n+- tool results only when they contain outcomes, failures, diffs, or important\n+  evidence\n+\n+The CLI should make that possible by preserving ordered records and clear record\n+kinds, not by deciding which record kinds are important.\n \n ### Optional Later Tool: `search`\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:44:00.727Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","s